n<br /> \n<br />4-H Clubs reach kids in every corner of Florida  from urban neighborhoods to suburban schoolyards to rural farming communities. \n<br /> \n<br />Demand for our services is growing. We now provide services to over 7,000 children! \n<br /> \n<br />The Collier County 4-H Association promotes positive youth development and supports local clubs and educational programs within Collier County with funds to engage children in the programs. \n<br /> \n<br />Educational programs provided by 4-H funding include but not limited too: \n<br />Camp Cloverleaf: 45 kids are sent per year to Lake Francis in Highlands County, the environment serves as a living laboratory. The camp is Monday-Friday and costs $300 per kid with transportation adding another $5,000. More details can be found by visiting, \n<a href=\"http://florida4h.org/camps_/cloverleaf/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://florida4h.org/camps_/cloverleaf/</a> \n<br /> \n<br />Ledge: Between 10-20 children are transported to Tallahassee, FL to learn about the government. Children can develop debate and public speaking skills, and analyze legislation. This civic education event requires $230 per person and $5,000 for education. More details can be found by visiting, \n<a href=\"http://florida4h.org/programsandevents_/leg/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://florida4h.org/programsandevents_/leg/</a>. \n<br /> \n<br />4-H University: 20 kids are able to attend this week-long event at the University of Florida in Gainesville, FL. The event allows kids to participate in educational workshops led by University of Florida. Costs include $250 per child and about $5,000 for transportation. For more information, visit 4huniversity.com/ \n<br /> \n<br />4-H Robotics Program: 5th graders in Collier County have the opportunity to build robots in class through 4-H! Children in last years program were able to study how to store frosting inside a robot, then program it to design cupcakes. Due to the high expenses of robot kits, only 6 robots are available for the 30 elementary schools that are covered by 4-H. More information can be found by visiting, \n<a href=\"https://4-h.org/parents/stem-agriculture/robotics/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://4-h.org/parents/stem-agriculture/robotics/</a> \n<br /><h3>Responsibilities</h3> PURPOSE: This unpaid internship consists of researching grant opportunities and writing grant proposals to support CC4H (Collier County 4-H Association). At the completion of the internship, the intern will have earned valuable experience in research, writing, and nonprofit fundraising. This position is ideal for an English, Communication, Sociology, or Womens/Gender Studies major who is looking to gain real-world experience in professional research and writing. \n<br />REPORTS TO: Director of Development \n<br />PRIMARY DUTIES: \n<br /> Utilize online tools to research available grant opportunities. \n<br /> Evaluate requests for proposals (RFPs) to determine applicability to CC4H programs and priorities. \n<br /> Pull together grant proposals including drafting, editing, revising, and proofreading. \n<br />QUALIFICATIONS: \n<br /> Excellent writing skills. \n<br /> Proficiency in Microsoft Office including PowerPoint, Excel and Word. \n<br />SKILLS DESIRED: \n<br /> Outgoing and well spoken \n<br /> A go-getter/pleasant personality \n<br /> Creative and detail-oriented \n<br /> Ability to exercise good judgment \n<br /> A can do attitude and desire to learn \n<br /> Ability to follow instructions and also work independently \n<br />BENEFITS: \n<br />Internships are unpaid and are designed to meet academic requirements, as applicable, and provide valuable real-world experience for participants. Successful completion of an internship may also yield letters of recommendation, a portfolio of their work when applicable, and important networking contacts. \n<br /> \n<br /><h2>Requirements</h2> Start and finish time is extremely flexible.'