ld vision for turning Sunnylands, their beloved winter home in the California desert, into the Camp David of the West, hosting American leaders  including seven presidents  and foreign dignitaries at Sunnylands for nearly half a century. They believed that Sunnylands could forever serve as a place where presidents, international leaders, and legislators with diverse perspectives could meet in peace to share ideas and find common ground.\r\n\r\nToday, retreats held at Sunnylands have included participants such as U.S. President Barack Obama, and more than a dozen international leaders, including President Xi Jinping of China, King Abdullah II of Jordan, and several ASEAN leaders. Whether held at the historic, 200-acre Annenberg estate in Rancho Mirage, California  with its iconic architecture and secluded setting  or in cities around the world, every retreat or meeting is designed to address and find solutions to real-world problems that promote peace, facilitate international agreement, and better serve the public good.\r\n<h3>Responsibilities</h3>\r\nResponsibilities will include, but are not limited to, conducting policy research, attending outside briefings/hearings in Washington, D.C., drafting memos, compiling daily news clips, planning and staffing private events, drafting correspondence, and performing administrative tasks for our office directors.\r\n<h2>Requirements</h2>\r\nSunnylands internships are a great experience for undergraduate students or recent graduates with a passion for international relations (with an emphasis on Asia and Latin America), strengthening democratic institutions, and promoting global health and food security.\r\n\r\nRequired Skills\r\n\r\n Good oral and written communication skills with an acute attention to detail;\r\n\r\n Ability to work cooperatively and courteously with others;\r\n\r\n Excellent organizational skills;\r\n\r\n Responsible, punctual, dependable;\r\n\r\n Ability to work independently and take initiative; and\r\n